---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const delivery = [
  ['No branding in the output', 'The generated project belongs in your delivery workflow, not on a Kilo invoice line.'],
  ['House style support', 'Naming conventions, folder structure, documentation format, macros, and test defaults can align to how your team works.'],
  ['Standard artefacts', 'SQL and dbt-style output that another consultant or internal team can pick up later.'],
  ['Training and review flow', 'Your team learns how to review, adapt, and defend the generated work rather than treating it as magic.'],
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Kilo for BI consultancies"
  description="Generate reviewable warehouse project foundations for BI and analytics consultancies."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">For BI consultancies</p>
    <h1>Stop spending the first half of the project on plumbing.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Generate a standard warehouse project in your house style so your team can
      spend more time on business logic, metric definitions, dashboards, and
      client judgement.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button" href="mailto:hello@example.com">Talk to us</a>
      <a class="button button-secondary" href="#white-label">White-label details</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-muted split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">The problem</p>
      <h2>Clients pay for expertise. Too many projects start with commodity build work.</h2>
      <p>
        Source-system interpretation, staging models, naming conventions, initial
        marts, docs, and tests are necessary. They are also repeatable enough
        that senior people should not do them from zero every time.
      </p>
      <p>Kilo gives your team an accelerator that still leaves the judgement with you.</p>
    </div>
    <aside class="note">
      <h3>Best fit</h3>
      <p>Consultancies that already deliver warehouse or BI projects and want faster starts without compromising reviewability or ownership.</p>
      <h3>The client-facing story</h3>
      <p>You deliver architecture, metric definitions, business interpretation, and adoption. Kilo handles a large share of the initial build base.</p>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="white-label">
    <p class="eyebrow">White-label delivery</p>
    <h2>The output should look like your best work.</h2>
    <div class="item-grid">
      {delivery.map(([title, text]) => (
        <article>
          <h3>{title}</h3>
          <p>{text}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section cta">
    <p class="eyebrow">First step</p>
    <h2>Trial it on a recent project shape.</h2>
    <p>The right test is whether Kilo can produce a starting project your team would actually review, adapt, and ship.</p>
    <a class="button" href="mailto:hello@example.com">Talk to us</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
